Jury nullification is one of those cultural myths that survives not
because it has any validity, but because some people just want to
believe in it no matter what, like crop circles and the hollow-earth
theory.

There is a tremendous amount of literature which purports to prove
that jury nullification is a valid legal principle.  Some of it sounds
very legalistic and therefore convincing.  All of it is smoke and
mirrors.

I'm not going to go into why the whole concept of the rule of law
would collapse if the logical consequences of jury nullification were
allowed to work themselves out.  You can search this newsgroup in
DejaNews.com for my posts on that topic if you are interested.

Here's the bottom line: the jury's function in a jury trial to make
findings on those issues of fact where reasonable doubt exists.  The
judge's function is to make findings on issues of law, and to
determine which issues of fact require decisions by the jury.

This principle has been part of common-law jurisprudence since the
common law developed in Norman England around the 12th century.  It is
about as deeply embedded in our modern legal system as anything can
be.

In practical terms, there is usually not much that the losing party or
the court can do about a jury verdict, because the jury does not have
to explain itself.  In that sense jury nullification is a "de facto"
jury power.  That does not make it legitimate, unless you accept the
principle that an act is legitimate if you can get away with it.

If a jury exercises its "de facto power" to return a verdict based on
its own interpretation of law, and the judge somehow finds out, she
will either enter the verdict she believes the jury SHOULD have
returned, or declare a mistrial.

There have been cases where jurors were subjected to contempt of court
rulings for returning a verdict based on jury nullification.  I have
not researched how such cases have turned out, but considering the
nature of the action, I think a contempt ruling is a natural and
justifiable response.
