The fact is that if you acquit, nobody can change that and
you can't be punished for it (assuming you didn't like on
your jury questionnaire or take a bribe or the like.)

Many people, myself included, believe that this is intentional
and is a feature, not a bug.  Even in situations where a blind
automaton would see the evidence and listen to the instructions
and then convict, according to the belief the jury provides a
check, that if the result would be unjust or immoral, the law
not be strictly applied to the particular solution.

This can also be used to cause injustice -- if the accused is
likable, or represents a point of view favorable to the juror,
he might get away with what ought to be punished.

In either case, when a jury does not convict because they
decide that a conviction or the punishment that would follow
would be unjust or immoral or otherwise wrong, even if the
accused has technically met all the points of the crime
accused; when the only rational explanation for the jury
acquitting is "We didn't want to convict" -- that is called
Jury Nullification.

You can find more information on the web.  Try
http://www.fija.org .

