I'll assume you're asking about the United States.

Jury nullification is when jurors decide their verdict in accordance
with the facts, as they find them, but contrary to the law.

The way trials work today, juries are given instructions by the judge
to follow the law, and they are sworn to do so.  They are told that
their verdict must be according to the law (as the judge explained
the law to them), and their job is to determine the facts of the case.
They decide who they think is lying, for example.  But since nobody can
really know what's inside a juror's head, and the juror can try to
make up any explanation that the judge will accept if questioned,
they can really vote any way they want.  Judges don't like this.
Historically, this power of the jurors has been important in some
cases, delivering what was widely viewed as proper justice, but it
is in conflict with the principle of the rule of law.  The fact that
you can't read the minds of jurors has always been a basic underlying
assumption in our system of trial by peers.

See U.S. v. Moylan 1969.

