Some people claim that Jury Nullification is an inherent right of
juries.  Others believe that it is an indication of "out of control
juries".

Probably the most famous case of Jury Nullification in the US is
Crown vs. Peter Zenger.  Zenger was accused of seditious libel for
criticizing the (English) governor of New York colony in his
newspaper.  The facts were not in dispute, nonetheless the jury
brought in a verdict of "not guilty".

For a defense of Jury Nullification, see
http://www.fija.org
and especially
http://www.fija.org/index.php?page=displaytxt&amp;id=31

For a more balanced discussion, see the Wikipedia article
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jury_nullification
