Presumably, you took an oath to decide the case according to the
judge's instructions.  I advise you to follow them.  To do otherwise
will expose you to penalties for contempt of court and possibly a
criminal conviction, depending on your state's law.

As to your friend's view on jury nullification, there is no clear
answer.  The fact is that there is nothing that can be done about a
"not guilty" verdict which flies in the face of the evidence.  The jury
has complete discretion to choose which witnesses to believe and which
to disbelieve.  The jury can even disbelieve uncontradicted testimony.
Since the burden of proof is on the state, a failure of proof means an
acquittal.  In a civil trial, the judge can enter a judgment opposite
to the jury's verdict.  But not in a criminal trial.  The judge can
change a "guilty" to a "not guilty", but not vice-versa.

Whether the resulting "jury nullification power" was intentionally
built into our justice system is a topic of debate.  Most authorities
have concluded that it was.  But most authorities have also concluded
that nullification cannot be requested or suggested to the jury, and
that the jury cannot be informed of its "power".  But I have heard tell
of judges that sneak it into the jury instructions, such as telling the
jury that if it finds beyond a reasonable doubt the defendant committed
the crime, the jury may convict (i.e., not the the jury "must"
convict).

Does jury nullification occur?  You bet it does.  Most people would
probably argue that the OJ Simpson verdict was a nullification.  There
was a locally famous case (in my area) in which it was undisputed that
the defendant started a bar fight and beat up the other guy.  The
defense attorney's entire closing argument was "it is UNAMERICAN to
convict the winner of a barroom brawl".  Verdict?  Not guilty.
