A little more care with the facts, please.

The Zenger case no doubt had a role in the adoption of the First Amendment,
but Zenger was tried only once.  The crown attempted to indict him twice
through a grand jury.  The grand juries refused to return a true bill, so
Cosby (the governor in question) went to the Supreme Court (of NY) and
obtained a bench warrant.  (Cosby had installed a compliant Chief Justice.)

In any case, the rule against double jeopardy was a long-standing part of
English common law and predated the Zenger case.

The rule that truth is a defense against libel is a construct of subsequent
state tort laws.  Truth was *not* a defense against seditious libel,
although Hamilton, Zenger's lawyer, argued the contrary.  That's why this
case is an example of jury nullification.  Zenger committed the act -- the
truth of the published statements was irrelevant -- but the jury refused to
convict.
