defendant, because those are different "offenses".  the language is:
nor shall any person be subject for the same offense to be twice
put in jeopardy of life or limb

If you stand on the California side of, say, Cal-Neva (a city on the
shore of Lake Tahoe) and shoot somebody on the Nevada side, you can be
tried twice:
. Once by California, for committing the murder there (firing the
shot)
. Once by Nevada, for committing the murder there (hitting and
killing the victim).

In addition, if the victim was a US Government Employee on duty, you
can be tried in Federal Court.  Similarly if you and the victim are of
different races or religions and the prosecution can prove to a jury
that you did it because of that difference.

I don't much like it either, but it's long-standing law, not something
they just made up for the Rodney King case.
