Sorry, but I have to disagree. Whether you're in favor of jury
nullification or not, that is not an example of it, not even
remotely.

"I don't believe the evidence" is a completely proper exercise of a
juror's function, because the Constitution and hundreds of years of
tradition make the jury the trier of facts. Whether a witness was
telling the truth is a matter of fact, not of law, and is up to the
jury to decide.

When the witness's testimony is allowed by the judge, that does not
mean it is accurate and must be accepted as accurate by the jury. It
*couldn't* mean that, since many trials contain witnesses who
contradict each other. It means it is relevant and the witness is
competent to present it, and then the jury, observing the witness,
must decide on the witness's credibility.

Jury nullification would be "I believe the evidence, and I conclude
beyond a reasonable doubt that he did the deed, but I'm still voting
not guilty."

