In Massachusetts, if the jury convicts court rules permit the
defendant to make a combined motion for acquittal or in the
alternative a new trial.  The judge may (must?) conditionally
grant or refuse a new trial at the same time that he enters
an appealable verdict of not guilty.  Both orders are subject
to simultaneous appellate review under their respective
standards.  In murder cases it is also common for the appeal
of conviction to be delayed until the defendant's first posttrial
motion for a new trial has been decided, and the appeals from
both actions decided together.

In general response to the thread, one might consider jury
nullification to be the counterpart of the prosecutor's power
to bring baseless or improperly motivated charges from
behind the shield of official immunity.

