Generally, a juror's duty to the state is to assess the facts and accept
the law, and he affirms his willingness to this.  But his promise is
given upon supposition that the state has done its duty to make the law
proper and acceptable to a reasonable person.  If the state has failed
in its duty to make the law acceptable to a reasonable person, the
juror's duty to accept the law is null and his promise is void.
