Just because evidence is accepted doesn't make it _credible_.  Only
the jurors can decide whether a given witness is lying, telling the
truth, or some of each -- and if a mixture, which parts to believe.

Remember, acceptance into the trial just means that the court has
decided that the evidence meets certain standards, in particular being
"generally accepted" in the Scientific Community.  But there still
needs to be a "foundation": testimony that connects the evidence to
the defendant.  And that testimony can be credible -- or not.

So if they decided that the (white) cop lied about finding the
evidence (on Simpson or at the crime scene), they would quite rightly
decide that there was not "proof beyond a reasonable doubt".  Of
course, if the jurors had that attitude a priori, it was the
responsibility of the DA and/or the judge to find it and excuse them
for cause.

