today, and the effect that accepting this principle would have on it.

When you evaluate the writings of the founders (or anyone else outside
your own time and place), it's important to consider the context in
which they lived.

The founders planned, prosecuted and justified a revolt against duly
constituted authority, and many of the ideas they expressed were
conditioned by that.  Consequently it's impossible to apply some of
their ideas to the modern world without accepting the proposition that
a similar revolt against our own duly constituted authority would be a
legitimate political act.  I can imagine circumstances in which I
would accept that proposition, but as things are now, I emphatically
do not.
